    context: 'Biodiversity — the variety of life on Earth — is in steep decline. Scientists estimate that the current rate of species extinction is between 100 and 1,000 times higher than natural background rates, leading many researchers to describe the present moment as the sixth mass extinction event in Earth\'s history.\n\nThe primary drivers of biodiversity loss are well documented: habitat destruction, overexploitation of species, pollution, climate change, and the spread of invasive species. Of these, habitat destruction — particularly the clearing of tropical rainforests — is considered the most significant. Rainforests cover less than 6 percent of the Earth\'s surface yet harbour more than half of all known species.\n\nThe consequences of biodiversity loss extend well beyond the loss of individual species. Ecosystems depend on complex webs of interaction, and the removal of even a single species can trigger cascading effects throughout the food chain. Furthermore, many of the medicines we rely on are derived from natural compounds found in plants and animals; their extinction could deprive us of discoveries yet to be made.',
